{"id":"1206.1170","submitter":"Leonhard L\\\"ucken","authors":"Leonhard L\\\"ucken, Jan Philipp Pade, Kolja Knauer, and Serhiy Yanchuk","title":"Reduction of Interaction Delays in Networks","comments":null,"journal-ref":"L. L\\\"ucken, J. P. Pade, K. Knauer and S. Yanchuk, \"Reduction of\n  interaction delays in networks\", EPL 103, 10006 (2013)","doi":"10.1209/0295-5075/103/10006","report-no":null,"categories":"math.DS nlin.PS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Delayed interactions are a common property of coupled natural systems and\ntherefore arise in a variety of different applications. For instance, signals\nin neural or laser networks propagate at finite speed giving rise to delayed\nconnections. Such systems are often modeled by delay differential equations\nwith discrete delays. In realistic situations, these delays are not identical\non different connections. We show that by a componentwise timeshift\ntransformation it is often possible to reduce the number of different delays\nand simplify the models without loss of information. We identify dynamic\ninvariants of this transformation, determine its capabilities to reduce the\nnumber of delays and interpret these findings in terms of the topology of the\nunderlying graph. In particular, we show that networks with identical sums of\ndelay times along the fundamental semicycles are dynamically equivalent and we\nprovide a normal form for these systems. We illustrate the theory using a\nnetwork motif of coupled Mackey-Glass systems with 8 different time delays,\nwhich can be reduced to an equivalent motif with three delays.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 6 Jun 2012 10:30:55 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 11 Jun 2015 11:31:07 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-12"}
